  "prompt": "What is the difference between enum, union and struct in C programming?",
  "response": "In C programming, `enum`, `union`, and `struct` are used to define data types, but they serve different purposes and behave in distinct ways. Here\u2019s a breakdown of each:\n\n### 1. `enum` (Enumeration)\n\nAn `enum` is a user-defined type that consists of a set of named integer constants. It is primarily used to represent a variable that can hold a set of predefined constants, enhancing code readability and maintainability.\n\n- **Definition**: An `enum` is defined using the `enum` keyword followed by a list of enumerator names.\n- **Memory**: Each enumerator is typically assigned an integer value, starting from 0 by default. The actual size of the `enum` type can vary based on the implementation but often matches the size of an `int`.\n  \n**Example:**\n```c\nenum Day { Sunday, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday };\nenum Day today = Wednesday; // today is assigned the value 3\n```\n\n### 2. `union`\n\nA `union` is a user-defined type that allows storing different data types in the same memory location. A union can hold only one of its non-static data members at a time, which means that the size of a union is determined by the size of its largest member.\n\n- **Definition**: A `union` is defined using the `union` keyword followed by a list of data members.\n- **Memory**: The size of the union is equal to the size of its largest member because it shares storage space among its members.\n  \n**Example:**\n```c\nunion Data {\n    int intValue;\n    float floatValue;\n    char charValue;\n};\nunion Data data;\ndata.intValue = 10;         // Now, data contains an integer\ndata.floatValue = 220.5;    // Now, data contains a float (intValue is now invalid)\n```\n\n### 3. `struct` (Structure)\n\nA `struct` is a user-defined type that allows grouping different data types into a single unit. It can hold multiple members (variables) of varying types, and each member can be accessed independently.\n\n- **Definition**: A `struct` is defined using the `struct` keyword followed by a list of members enclosed in braces.\n- **Memory**: The size of a structure is the sum of the sizes of its members, possibly accounting for padding for alignment.\n  \n**Example:**\n```c\nstruct Person {\n    char name[50];\n    int age;\n    float height;\n};\nstruct Person john; // A variable john of type Person\njohn.age = 30;      // Set age\n```\n\n### Summary of Differences\n\n| Feature       | `enum`                       | `union`                            | `struct`                          |\n|---------------|------------------------------|------------------------------------|-----------------------------------|\n| Purpose       | Define named constants        | Store different data types         | Group different data types        |\n| Members       | Integer constants             | Only one active member at a time | Multiple members of differing types|\n| Memory Usage  | Size of integer (usually 4 bytes) | Size of largest member               | Sum of sizes of all members (plus padding if needed) |\n| Access        | Accessed by name             | Accessed via member name (only one valid at a time) | Accessed via member names |\n\nIn summary, `enum` is used for defining a set of named constants, `union` is for storing different data types in the same memory location, and `struct` is for creating a complex data type that encompasses multiple variables of different types.",
